Title: SymWriter doesn't support deterministic compilation
History:
To Whom may concern,
In

From 10-10-2018, the buddy build get failure as
295>CSC : error CS0041: Unexpected error writing debug information -- 'SymWriter doesn't support deterministic compilation' [E:\bt\975727\repo\src\xstore\watask\Tools\Deployment\ValidateReservedIPs\ValidateReservedIPs.csproj]

The last commit of mentioned project was on 09-20-2018, so there is no change recently to that project. And ?SymWriter? is not from any source code of that project.

Do you know what is this ?SymWriter? came from and why it suddenly has conflict with ?true? in .csproj file?

Thank you,
Tony.



Created by: Tony Wang (tonywa@microsoft.com) Charlie Wickham (Charlie.Wickham@microsoft.com) says:

I looked for this and found a better explanation (sort of) as to what this means. The compiler team has augmented this error code to a DLL is missing (Microsoft.DiaSymWriter.Native..dll or something like that). For now, since all
our builds are broken, we should just remove that (@Fab Tillier this was in your validate IPs
deployment tool: did you set that purposefully?). I?ve disabled it in one of my branches and just submitted a buddy. We can see where that goes.

Fab: did you create this project with VS2017? Doesn?t look like it but checking?

c

Charlie Wickham (Charlie.Wickham@microsoft.com) says:

Should be DiaSymReader (which includes the writer). In any case, I am finding it corext build packages so there is something else we probably need to enable in the build in order for this DLL to be available to the compiler. I still vote
for turning it off until someone can devote some time to figuring out why.

c

Tony Wang (tonywa@microsoft.com) says:

I have confirmed that by flipping ?Deterministic? to false in
ValidateReservedIPs.csproj can solve this issue.

Fab Tillier (ftillier@microsoft.com) says:

I did create the project initially with VS2017, and then had to manually edit it to make the tools version compatible with our build system. I have no problem turning it off, not even sure why it?s there? Certainly wasn?t purposeful.

-Fab

Charlie Wickham (Charlie.Wickham@microsoft.com) says:

The missing DLL needs to get on the path or in some property such that the compiler can find it when writing the pdb file. Might need a msbuild.corext version upgrade.

c

Matthew Christopher (matthchr@microsoft.com) says:

This is breaking master and we?re trying to start a release, so I sent a PR here to remove Deterministic from the project (presuming that fixes it):
https://msazure.visualstudio.com/One/One%20(Empty%20Default)/_git/Batch-Service/pullrequest/1156080?_a=overview

Thanks,
-Matt

Charlie Wickham (Charlie.Wickham@microsoft.com) says:

The weird thing is that it passes locally so something is amiss between local and official.

c

Matthew Christopher (matthchr@microsoft.com) says:

It passes in quickbuild too (else the PR gate would've blocked it).
I removed it from the project though and the build passes again.
-Matt
